[b]Signal Quality Engine [WavesUnchained][/b]

[b]What it does[/b]

A range-fade signal engine for commodities, futures, stocks and indices. One thing done well: it fades the range edges — long the exhausted lows, short the exhausted highs — when the market is ranging, price is stretched from the mean, structure says "edge", and a candle rejects. A regime gate (ADX + EMA slope) stands the tool down in strong trends, so it never fades a trend pullback. No regime switching, no multi-timeframe machinery — a single, legible logic with an Edge → Setup → Watch → Trigger read.

[b]The one logic[/b]

Price stretched to an edge (distance + structure) → momentum turns back off the edge → candle rejects → score high enough → Trigger.

[list]
[*][b]Edge[/b] — which side is exhausted (the dominant top/bottom exhaustion score). Shown as Low → Long, High → Short, or Mid-range.
[*][b]Setup[/b] (faint gray triangle) — exhaustion building at an edge
[*][b]Watch[/b] (bright yellow triangle) — the exhaustion score has reached its threshold; a rejection is still pending
[*][b]Trigger[/b] (label) — a candle rejects and the score clears the threshold
[/list]

The dashboard Status line names the active tier (Mid-range / Exhaustion building / Watch — rejection pending / Trigger active).

[b]Exhaustion score (0–100)[/b]

[list]
[*][b]Distance[/b] (40%) — how far price is stretched past the mean (EMA-ATR + Bollinger-Z)
[*][b]Structure[/b] (30%) — recent high/low proximity, wick rejection, close beyond the band
[*][b]Momentum[/b] (30%) — RSI / StochRSI / WaveTrend overbought–oversold extreme
[/list]

Strictness presets (Very Strict / Strict / Balanced) set both the exhaustion threshold and the cooldown. Market profiles are asset-aware: they set band width, edge proximity and the regime tolerance (how trendy the tape can be and still be faded) — commodities mean-revert through choppy trends and fade readily, indices trend persistently and get a stricter range filter. A momentum window keeps a turn valid for a few bars, so a one-bar timing miss doesn't void the setup.

[b]On the chart[/b]

[list]
[*]Mean (EMA50) and the upper/lower bands, with a light range-channel fill and an outer-edge zone tint (where a fade can trigger)
[*]Compact LONG / SHORT fade labels with the exhaustion score (full detail on hover)
[*]Faint gray triangle = exhaustion building, bright yellow triangle = watch (rejection near) — same direction as the eventual signal
[*]ATR risk levels — SL beyond the edge, TP1 at the mean, TP2 at the opposite band
[*]Confirmed swing-high / -low pivot markers as a control reference only — they never influence which signals fire
[*]Light-theme dashboard with edge, status, action and both exhaustion scores
[/list]

[b]Alerts[/b]

[list]
[*]SQE Long Signal, SQE Short Signal, SQE Any Signal, SQE Watch (an edge exhausting toward a rejection)
[/list]

[b]Note[/b]

This is a range-fade tool by design. In a strong trend it is intentionally quiet rather than fading every push — use a trend tool there.

